To confirm the suitability of the designed device for accurate and reproducible assay of NFZ, uniform illumination of the paper-based analytical device inside the imaging box was tested. Fig. 7
                        a shows the image of a paper-based analytical device prepared by coating all detection zones with GQDs only. The RSD% of the obtained G values for the different detection zones in the paper-based analytical device was ≤ 1.6% indicating the uniform light distribution within the device. Then, different concentrations of NFZ were spotted in the detection zones. The captured images were analyzed by RGB color detector software. The green (G) value showed a good correlation with drug concentrations (Fig. 7b). The calibration curve was constructed for NFZ by plotting NFZ concentration versus G0/G, where G0 and G are the G values for blank and samples, respectively. The method showed excelling linearity for NFZ (Fig. 7c) over the range of 0.4 – 30 nmol/zone (r = 0.996) with a very good sensitivity down to 0.12 nmol/zone (Table 4
                        ). The developed method was found to have excellent analytical merits of linearity and sensitivity. Thus, the proposed method can be applied in the future for the on-site determination of NFZ in quality control laboratories and for manufacturing companies.
